  "prompt": "How difficult is it get into RSI?",
  "response": "The Research Science Institute (RSI) is extremely competitive and challenging to get into. Here are some key factors contributing to its difficulty:\n\n1. **High Achieving Applicants**: RSI attracts a global pool of top-performing high school students, especially those who demonstrate exceptional abilities and achievements in science, technology, engineering, and mathematics (STEM).\n\n2. **Low Acceptance Rate**: Typically, RSI has a low acceptance rate, accepting around 80 students each year from thousands of applicants worldwide.\n\n3. **Rigorous Selection Criteria**: The selection process considers academic excellence, standardized test scores (often exceptionally high SAT/ACT scores), teacher recommendations, and significant achievements or awards in science/math competitions.\n\n4. **Research Experience**: Many successful applicants have prior research experience or have demonstrated a strong interest in and aptitude for scientific inquiry and research.\n\n5. **Holistic Review**: RSI looks for well-rounded candidates who possess not only academic excellence but also leadership potential, motivation, creativity, and a genuine passion for research.\n\n6. **Thoughtful Essays**: The application often requires essays where students must articulate their interest in research and how they can contribute to and benefit from the RSI experience.\n\nOverall, gaining admission to RSI requires a combination of outstanding academic credentials, genuine passion for science and research, and well-crafted application materials. Preparing early and demonstrating a consistent and deep commitment to STEM can improve an applicant\u2019s chances.",
